and democratic systems, and how such performances reshape understandings of the role of politics. Staging Democracy moves beyond Russia and Ukraine to offer a novel economic argument for why some people support Putin and similar politicians. Pisano suggests we can analyze politics in both democracies and authoritarian regimes using the same analytical lens of political theater.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aPolitical culturezRussia (Federation) 0aPolitical culturezRussia (Federation). 0aPolitical culturezUkraine. 0aPolitical participationxEconomic aspectszRussia (Federation) 0aPolitical participationxEconomic aspectszRussia (Federation). 0aPolitical participationxEconomic aspectszUkraine. 0aPublic relations and politicszRussia (Federation) 0aPublic relations and politicszRussia (Federation). 0aPublic relations and politicszUkraine. 4aPerforming Arts & Drama. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  apolitical theatre in russia and ukraine, electoral fraud in russia, election corruption in ukraine, capitalism and democracy, why do people support putin, economic collapse in russia and ukraine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075182608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2022 Englishz978311099296008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2022z9783110992939oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176408040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501764080423Coveruhtt